@CiaranoBeachain I will of course but I am a case in point - they said three to four months - I am newly diagnosed (since Feb) and definitely over 18! I thought it didn’t extend to Type 2 and that’s what needs to change - but I’m new to all this and will check it out 👍

8/8 There are over a quarter of a million people in Ireland with diabetes, over half a billion worldwide, a lifelong condition listed by @WHO as one of the top ten leading causes of deaths globally. And the rates are increasing year on year.
#diabetesawareness #knowledgeispower

7/8 The novelty might wear off but for now it’s the best accessory and i will proudly be showing it off as often as i can.
Now for some frightening stats… #diabetes @Diabetes_ie

6/8 In Ireland the HSE supplies this device to Type 1 Diabetics (but we need to do more to extend to Type 2 that need it). A great diabetic nurse at the #bonssecours gave me a tutorial today and now i can’t stop checking my phone.. and not to check up on social media 😅 @dexcom

5/8 It monitors my glucose continuously and sends it via bluetooth to an app on my phone that gives me up to the minute data - and also sends it on to my diabetic health care team. It alerts me if my bloods are going too low or too high and no more impromtu fainting hopefully 😊

4/8 And then came the gamechanger - that little transmitter is called a Dexcom G6 - it will revolutionise my diabetes management and empower me to make better judgements and best of all no more fingersticks! @dexcom @Diabetes_ie

3/ 8 I live my life using smart technology that I barely think about, an app for car parking, booking a taxi, ordering groceries, managing my heating.. a wealthy few are engaged in a race to space for goodness sake. And here I was sticking a pin in my fingers to test my blood 😬

2/8 I think i would make a very good burglar right now as my finger tips have been pricked constantly since February as I test (sometimes up to 10 times a day given my blood instability) for ketones and sugars. But i’d like to keep my finger prints intact 😬 #type1diabetes
1/8 My life just changed for the better… and all because of that little transmitter on my arm. They say knowledge is power and it’s so true #type1diabetes @dexcom https://t.co/EX0byrDejn

Because stars are only a vast collection of matter – it is only the tumultuous reactions of that spinning and thumping that releases the energy and creates the light that shines so brightly we can see it here on earth. 
Let our stars shine on #WorldCancerDay2022
The light installation was so important to him. Yet if you analyse it – decompose it - what it amounts to is a light shining through pinpricks on paper. But the key is the light – the illumination.

It was during one of those long moments of silence that Richard paused and said “I believe in star dust” – it was a phrase that he repeated often after that – a sort of mantra that gave him the grit to see through those terrible days
Dara would try to tell him something funny - trying to find normality in the tragic circumstances that led to his wonderful strong dad making that painful journey. Sometimes we ran out of words.

Some evenings we remained there for 30 minutes or more as he steadfastly made his way purposefully up those stairs – refusing all offers of help. Most of these journeys would begin with Dara and myself encouraging him, distracting him.

Richard had cancer in most of his major organs but it was the cancer in his spine that was the most debilitating
And as it became harder for him to climb those stairs he would stare at that installation as he paused to catch his breath and gather his strength to take another step

In my house I have this light installation by artist Oisin Byrne called “we are stardust”.  It’s a magical recreation of two people intertwined in starlight and it has always lived at the top of the stairs leading to our bedroom.

Knowing that his time was short, Richard became increasingly fond of the idea of stardust, a comfort that he would re-join the cosmos from whence he came. Sending hugs to all who live with and beyond cancer and those, like me, who miss the stars we have lost  #worldcancerday https://t.co/u5rjTKaAhd

5/5 I imagined a shoe from my own childhood when I painted this today, it resonated with me and maybe someday a much better artist will do it justice
 #theblueshoe #tuam #motherandbabyhomes #commissionofinvestigation

4/5 And here it is...

‘Finally, the remains of a blue shoe from a young juvenile was present near the northern end of the tank’ 

I wondered did a loving mother put those shoes on her child on that fateful day, buried with those little blue shoes and so little dignity

3/5 A stark reminder that those sewage tanks were the final resting place for little children from just weeks old up to the age of three. I wrote it down so I would never forget that one line that stood in stark contrast to the complex scientific findings of the excavation.

2/5 This interim report (5th) of the #CommissionofInvestigation focussed on burial practices following an osteoarchaeological assessment of the underground tanks. In the midst of the detailed and detached analysis of bone fragments there was this one sentence which made me stop.

1/5 The blue shoe and why it mattered so much..

The threat of countries losing routes due to the pandemic needs to be considered in the context of a highly profitable and competitive industry where there has been, and will inevitably be, those who don’t survive and those who do.
In the meantime give people their money back

There are many sectors deeply impacted by the pandemic - while the airline industry is hyper competitive it has been among the first to push for bailouts. Commercial airline profits were $25+ billion in 2019 - with 4.5 billion passengers globally, twice that of a decade ago

People who paid for flights with cash are entitled to have their money back. Governments working together to change the law to allow airlines to keep people’s money is patently wrong. If customers are happy to take vouchers that’s their choice but many may well need the cash

This is wrong on so many levels - airlines need to look to their shareholders to keep them afloat not customers or governments #givecashrefund
